  "text": "Tributyltin is the most studied group of OT compounds for all toxicological aspects, including its effects on the pulmonary system. Van Loveren et al. [CITATION_1] showed that rats exposed to a diet containing up to 80 mg/kg of tributyltin oxide (TBTO) have suppressed NK cells activity in the lungs, which have an important role in surveillance, evident against neoplastic and virus-infected targets [CITATION_2] . This potential immunotoxicity in the lungs could favor respiratory viral infections and neoplasms. Contrasting these findings, Carthew et al. [CITATION_3] examined whether the exposure of rats to TBTO exacerbated the type of pneumonia caused by pneumonia virus of mice and Mycoplasma [CITATION_4] . Animals were exposed for 6 weeks to TBTO in the diet, in a similar protocol employed by Van Loveren et al. [CITATION_5] . Although other signs of TBTO toxicity were found, such as a reduction as a reduction in body and thymus weights, as well as the development of cholangitis, there was no evidence that this OTs favored the occurrence of pneumonia in the animals.",
